e Christianities have diverged so much in their core values that they ought to be thought of as two separate religions. The authors draw on both quantitative data and interviews to uncover how progressive and conservative Christians determine with whom they align themselves religiously, and how they distinguish themselves from each other. They find that progressive Christians emphasize political agreement relating to social justice issues as they determine who is part of their in-group, and focus less on theological agreement. Among conservative Christians, on the other hand, the major concern is whether one agrees with them on core theological points. Progressive and conservative Christians thus use entirely different factors in determining their social identity and moral values.In a time when religion and politics have never seemed so intertwined, One Faith No Longer offers a timely and compelling reframing of an age-old conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and politicszUnited States. 0aChristianityzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aAffinity.  aAmerican Christianity.  aAmerican National Elections Survey.  aAttitudes toward Islam.  aAttitudes toward Muslims.  aBaptists.  aBias against Conservative Christians.  aBible.  aBiblical Inerrancy.  aBlogs.  aCatholic Protestant Conflict.  aChrislam.  aChristian Identity.  aConservative Christianity.  aConservative Christians.  aContent Analysis.  aCultural Toolkit.  aCulture War.  aDoctrine.  aEvangelicalism.  aEvangelicals.  aFlexible Theology.  aFundamentalist Christians.  aHell.  aHinduism Buddhism Conflict.  aHistorical Theology.  aHumanism.  aHumanistic Ethic of Social Justice.  aImmigration Reform.  aInterviews.  aIslamophobia.  aModerate Christians. 